<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1465,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1501,1526]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Remarks.</emphasis>
Adults of 
<taxonomicName box="[435,541,1501,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[435,541,1501,1526]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display golden-brown background color with darker pigmentation on the head, thorax (
<figureCitation box="[245,387,1537,1562]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[211,1383,297,1177]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1218]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Perlesta browni. a–b, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River; c–d, Arkansas, Ouachita River; a, c, male, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; b, d, female, head + pronotum, dorsal profile." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301372/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 3a‒3d</figureCitation>
), and abdomen. Whereas the abdominal terga for females are nearly uniform in color throughout their length, by comparison male terga 6‒10 are markedly darker than the anterior five segments. The posterolateral corners of the male 9th sternum are clothed by a dense matting of long hairs, noticeably longer and denser than the anterolateral and medial portions of the segment (
<figureCitation box="[932,1020,1648,1673]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Fig. 4d</figureCitation>
). Males have long, slender, tubular paraprocts with a mesoapical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[560,692,1684,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 4a‒4c</figureCitation>
) that are similar to sympatric 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[1032,1160,1685,1708]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[1032,1160,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1176,1305,1684,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[175,1408,392,1789]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,375,1820]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Perlesta cinctipes. a–b, Arkansas, unknown locality; c–f, Missouri, South Moreau Creek; a, c, male, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; b, d, female, head + pronotum, dorsal profile; e, right paraproct, lateral view, 180X; f, right paraproct, lateral view, 330X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301376/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 5e‒5f</figureCitation>
) but longer than those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Grubbs &amp; Dewalt, 2018" authorityName="Grubbs &amp; Dewalt" authorityYear="2018" box="[310,449,1721,1744]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armitagei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[310,449,1721,1744]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. armitagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[460,552,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[460,552,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[570,708,1720,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1683,1705]" captionTargetBox="[179,1408,214,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1659]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Perlesta armitagei sp. nov., male.; a, Ohio, Deer Creek, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; b, Indiana, Blue River, right paraproct, lateral, 370X; c, Pennsylvania, French Creek, paraprocts, dorsal, 450X; d, Pennsylvania, French Creek, paraprocts, caudal, 330X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301380/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 7a, 7c</figureCitation>
). In addition, 
<bibRefCitation box="[873,1170,1720,1745]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart (1991)</bibRefCitation>
showed that 
<taxonomicName box="[1327,1435,1720,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[1327,1435,1720,1745]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
femora are pigmented only in the distal third, the brown color extending to the articulation with the tibia (their Fig. 344). Conversely, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[359,489,1793,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[359,489,1793,1816]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
femora are pigmented in approximately the middle 40%, the articulations with the coxae and tibiae are unpigmented (
<bibRefCitation box="[542,985,1828,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart 1991, their Fig. 342</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1465,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">
Females can be separated by characteristics of their subgenital plate lobes and median notch (
<bibRefCitation box="[1246,1374,1864,1889]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
). The eggs of 
<taxonomicName box="[245,353,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[245,353,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are easily differentiated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[707,837,1901,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[707,837,1901,1924]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The egg of 
<taxonomicName box="[990,1098,1900,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[990,1098,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a short, slightly distallyflanged ribbed collar and the chorionic surface is covered by fine punctations except near the eclosion line (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1659,1681]" captionTargetBox="[180,1392,226,1590]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Perlesta browni, Arkansas, Fourche La Fave River. a, male, paraprocts, lateral view, 300X; b, male, paraprocts, caudal (left) and mostly lateral (right) views, 330X; c, male, right paraproct, lateral view 270X; d, male, 9 th sternum, 130X; e, egg, 330X; f, egg collar, anterior pole, 1100X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301374/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">Figs. 4e‒4f</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[231,358,1972,1997]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8452" refString="Stark, B. P. (1989) Perlesta placida (Hagen), an eastern Nearctic species complex (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Insect Systematics and Evolution, 20, 263 - 286. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 X 00339" type="journal article">Stark 1989</bibRefCitation>
, his Fig. 15). The egg of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[655,785,1973,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[655,785,1973,1996]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="86">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar collar but the chorionic surface is coarsely pitted except for the smooth eclosion line region (
<bibRefCitation box="[707,834,2008,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8452" refString="Stark, B. P. (1989) Perlesta placida (Hagen), an eastern Nearctic species complex (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Insect Systematics and Evolution, 20, 263 - 286. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 X 00339" type="journal article">Stark 1989</bibRefCitation>
, his Fig. 17; 
<bibRefCitation box="[979,1103,2008,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="86" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
, his Figs. 7.394‒7.396).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="87" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName box="[199,379,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[199,379,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Perlesta browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered endemic to the Interior Highland region (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1139,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox="[205,1400,405,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[167,1431,373,1925]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Distribution maps of Perlesta based on material examined during this study. a, P. adena, P. browni, P. cinctipes, and P. xube; b, P. armitagei sp. nov. The record from northern West Virginia (red circle; Tarter &amp; Nelson 2006) is conditional since that material was not available for study. The type locality is represented by the purple circle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301388/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Fig. 11a</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1153,1431,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" refId="ref8347" refString="Poulton, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. (1991) Stoneflies of the Ozark and Ouachita Mountains (Plecoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 13, 1 - 116. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 38911829" type="journal article">Poulton &amp; Stewart 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,276,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" refId="ref8501" refString="Stark, B. P. (2004) Perlidae (The Stones). In: Stark, B. P. &amp; Armitage, B. J. (Eds.), The stoneflies (Plecoptera) of eastern North America. Vol. II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Bulletin of the Ohio Biological Survey. New Series. Uol. 14. Ohio Biological Society, Columbus, Ohio, pp. 61 - 148." type="journal article">Stark 2004</bibRefCitation>
) until specimens seemingly indistinguishable from this species were reported from a single locality in eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[239,330,223,248]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Virginia</collectingRegion>
(Kondratieff 
<emphasis box="[489,548,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">et al.</emphasis>
2011). 
<taxonomicName box="[637,817,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="browni">
<emphasis box="[637,817,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Perlesta browni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Stark" authorityYear="2004" box="[1034,1163,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipes">
<emphasis box="[1034,1163,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">P. cinctipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly in the Ouachita Mountain region of western 
<collectingRegion box="[469,573,260,285]" country="United States of America" name="Arkansas" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Arkansas</collectingRegion>
and eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[715,832,260,285]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[847,941,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox="[205,1400,405,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[167,1431,373,1925]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Distribution maps of Perlesta based on material examined during this study. a, P. adena, P. browni, P. cinctipes, and P. xube; b, P. armitagei sp. nov. The record from northern West Virginia (red circle; Tarter &amp; Nelson 2006) is conditional since that material was not available for study. The type locality is represented by the purple circle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1301388/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="87">Fig. 11a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
